> ask Percy about Lower Hemmingwedge-on-the-Fritz

> ask Percy about Lower Hemmingwedge-on-the-Fritz
"It's a beautiful little hamlet on the river," says Percy, "Just the perfect vacation spot."

"How'd a rat get ta be a viscount there?" you ask.

"Why, I inherited the position, of course.  From my father and his father before him."

"Oh. Alright." That doesn't really answer the question all that well, you think.
> take shoe

> take shoe
You pick it up.
You pull the sizzling shoe out of the fire and blow on it briefly to cool it off before pulling out the lace in one fluid motion and dropping it in front of Percy. Then you bite off a hunk of toe with your teeth.

"Hey Percy," you say, "Lookit this. Ahhhhhh!" Giggling, you open your mouth to display a mouthful of chewed leather. It's the sort of mischievous little prank that you like to pull, the sort of thing that's earned you the ire of the Urchinfinder General -- enough to be Public Enemy Number Two, at least.

Percy rolls his eyes. "Yes, Rags, very droll."

That's when you hear it. A slow, steady appreciative clap.  Someone out there in the woods, right outside the glow of your campfire, is applauding your display.

"Whozzat?" you snarl, your body instinctively tensing in case you need to make a run for it.  Urchinfinder patrols usually don't come this far into the forest, and the usual cops, Pinkertons and railyard bulls wouldn't be out this late at night...but...you never know...

“Bravo, bravo, good show,” says the stranger moving into the light of your fire. “Excellently funny stuff, my dear girl.”

You’ve never seen anyone quite like this before.  He’s tall and thin like a scarecrow, his arms and legs moving like he has too many extra joints, but his head is oddly flattened like a rotten jack-o’-lantern that’s been kicked in. But from his fancy embroidered red jacket and gold buttons to his towering black top hat, you know he must be someone of consequence. Fancy people always dress like that.

Well.  At least he seems to appreciate good mischief.

“Just a capital performance and I would know,” he continues, “Seeing as I AM in the performance business."

"You wouldn’t mind if I joined you for just a titch now, would you?"
1: Yes
2: No
> 1

“I think you best keep on movin’, stranger,” you say.

“Oh, of course, how rude of me, I haven’t introduced myself,” he says, ignoring your words as he sits on the log opposite you. “But I’m sure that once I do, you’ll be begging me to stay.”

“But please, you don’t even know who I am yet.”

He extends a preternaturally long arm that seems to unfurl forever, his long thin fingers offering you a small business card.  Warily, you take it from his grasp.

Not much good to you, since you can't read.

"It says ' T.I. Urge'," whispers Percy helpfully. “Ringmaster, Urge & Silent Partners’ Carnival of Regrets.”

“Ringmaster? Carnival? Is you some kind of circus man?”

“Not just SOME kind of circus man!” says T.I. Urge. “The Carnival of Regrets is only the greatest traveling show on earth, with thrills to chill you and chills to thrill you! Sights that will amaze even the most jaded urchin, yes, even you, my dear girl! And best of all, the Carnival of Regrets is always recruiting new talent.”

“New talent?”

“Yes, my dear girl, new talent like you! I saw your little chewed food display and, let me tell you, you don’t see mischievous comedy chops like that everyday! I think YOU would make the perfect addition to our happy traveling family. I know some clowns who would love to meet you. And, of course, we can appreciate someone with the talent for mayhem and mischief to become Public Enemy Number Two.”

“I SHOULD be one,” you say, "But I ain’t never thought about joinin’ no circus."

“Oh pish posh! What child hasn’t dreamed of running away to join the circus? The glamour! The adventure! And, dare I say it, the food! You certainly won’t have to settle for shoe leather when you’re part of our circus family. You’ll be eating funnel cakes and corn dogs everyday!”

“Cor! That sounds like the elephant’s in-step!” you cry, your head swimming at the idea. Wow! Food – REAL food – everyday!

“Rags, I must strongly caution you against this,” says Percy, “This all seems very suspect. I don’t know that we can trust this fellow to be on the level.”

“Oh I understand, you need a little time to think about it, discuss it with your…er…rat there,” says T.I. Urge. “But certainly, there’s no harm in just coming to the carnival, right? To see it for yourself? We’re setting up tomorrow and I’ve got a special golden ticket right here in my vest, just one special ticket for one lucky little child, that will get through the doors before the grand opening…”

He plucks a shimmering golden ticket from his vest pocket.

“Oo! I want it!” you cry, snatching it from his fingers. “Besides, Percy, he’s right, ain’t no harm in just LOOKING at a carnival, huh?”

“Excellent!” says Urge, rubbing his bony hands together. “Well, my dear girl, we’ll look forward to seeing you tomorrow. And once you get a glimpse of our carnival, I’m sure you’ll never want to leave…”

Carnival of Regrets. November 13, 1929.

The wooden fence surrounding the carnival is covered with old posters and advertisements, mostly left over from previous fairs and events.  You can see the spire of the carnival's Big Top tent rising over the fence, and you can faintly hear the tell-tale "doodle doodle doot doot doodle doodle doot doot" of a drunken calliope.

You are at the Grand Entrance.
The entryway to the carnival is through the mouth of a giant, grinning plywood face with a handlebar mustache and spinning swirly eyes.  You can hear faint calliope music coming from beyond.  There's also a ticket booth. Inside sits a fat greasy man in a tank top, smoking a limp cigarette.  He regards you with contempt when you look at him.
You can see a ticket booth and a wanted poster.
You can go north.
